instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The system follows a pipeline architecture: physical robot measurements are published via MQTT and received by an Asset Administration Shell (AAS) executor, which stores measured, simulated and reference values in a digital shadow hosted on ThingsBoard. The digital shadow combines a SysML model of the robot’s structure with executable simulation models (e.g., Simulink) that compute friction behavior. The pipeline automatically triggers the simulation runs, updates the shadow, and forwards results to a visualization dashboard."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle follows the MBSE abstraction hierarchy described in Document 1: (i) Requirements stage, (ii) Functional‑architecture stage, (iii) Logical‑architecture stage, and (iv) Product/Technical (implementation) stage. Early‑stage artefacts are expressed as high‑level SysML requirement and block diagrams; the functional stage adds SysML internal‑block diagrams and behavioural state‑machine extensions; the logical stage refines the system into component‑connector ADL models such as ACME, AADL or MontiArc (including MontiArc‑Automaton for behaviour); the product stage materialises the models in simulation tools (e.g., Simulink) or executable code and generates concrete data‑trace artifacts that constitute the digital shadow. Transition between stages is governed by explicit traceability links – the “originates‑from” association defined in Document 2 – which map each data‑trace to its generating processing component, input traces and the underlying calculation or simulation model. Conformance to the Digital‑Shadow Reference Model is ensured by a mapping relation that binds concrete class‑diagrams to the reference concepts (Document 2), providing lifecycle governance through model‑to‑model conformance checking and traceability."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is addressed by combining physics‑based (white‑box) models with data‑driven (black‑box) models. The reliability of the shadow depends on the correctness of the underlying models and the data transformations applied. The approach emphasizes traceability of data traces to the models and processing components via the ‘originates‑from’ association, which supports verification of model transformations (e.g., from SysML to simulation models). Validation activities focus on ensuring transformation correctness and maintaining traceability throughout the data processing chain."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "Communication between the physical robot and the digital shadow is realised through an MQTT publish‑subscribe network. An MQTT broker mediates the exchange, using JSON‑encoded messages on hierarchically organised topics; the broker can enforce read/write permissions per topic. The AAS Executor accesses the Asset Administration Shell via its defined interfaces (e.g., standard AAS APIs) to retrieve the incoming sensor data and to publish the constructed digital‑shadow model. Processed shadow data are forwarded to the ThingsBoard IoT platform for persistence and visualisation. The described stack thus comprises MQTT as the transport protocol, JSON as the payload format, hierarchical topic naming for logical separation, and AAS‑based integration for semantic linking."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "Integration uses MQTT as the data‑exchange protocol, allowing IoT devices to stream sensor data to the digital twin. The digital shadow is persisted and visualized in ThingsBoard, an open‑source IoT platform. Interoperability is achieved through the Asset Administration Shell (AAS) as a standardized container, and model integration is performed by coupling SysML structural models with Simulink behavioral models via the Functional Mock‑up Interface (FMI). These standards enable the digital twin to interoperate with enterprise IoT infrastructure and other digital twins."
